  <body>
    <outline text="&amp;lt;RelevantExerptedExistingContext&amp;gt;">
      <outline text="1">
        <outline text="So I think it's defining the container of the website and then of the wedding. Sorry, forget the website. It's like defining the container for the, what do we call it, the wish-fulfilling jewel. Maybe I'll call it that, why not? And then for the wedding track, it's to design the container for that as well. I guess the job is to figure out which one's first. Maybe we just do the website one because it's simpler. We'll do the wedding one, which is much more complicated because we know a lot. I want to dig through the research. And then we can, anything that we learn from there can go back to the container. This feels kind of more manageable and we'll make some good progress and you can send something to Andrew. It lets me work incrementally.">
          <outline text="I like this sequencing. It feels grounded, not forced. Start with the wish-fulfilling jewel container because it's simpler and you've already lived through it with Nabil — you have a real case to work from, not hypotheticals. Get something to Andrew. Then go deeper on the wedding track where there's richer research to mine, and let insights flow back." />
          <outline text="The incremental part matters. You're not trying to get it all right at once. You're building a draft container that's good enough to react to." />
          <outline text="So let's co-think on the wish-fulfilling jewel container right now. From what I absorbed in the calls, here's what we're defining:" />
          <outline text="Who it's for — the person with an unclear felt sense who just wants someone to handle it. Not the DIY Squarespace person. Not the Shopify daily-manager." />
          <outline text="Who it's not for — anyone who needs e-commerce, complex backends, user auth" />
          <outline text="What happens — you get on a call, extract their implying, build the thing live or near-live, deliver" />
          <outline text="What they get — a static (or Airtable-backed) site that's live and theirs" />
          <outline text="Pricing — initial build + optional maintenance" />
          <outline text="Boundaries — what's in scope, what's not (the bun sizes for changes)" />
          <outline text="Want to think through these together right now, one by one? Or would you rather I draft something from what I already know and you react to it — more like editing clay than sculpting from nothing?Either way works. The first is more alive co-thinking; the second is faster and you might prefer reacting to something concrete. What feels right?" />
        </outline>
      </outline>
      <outline text="2">
        <outline text="" />
        <outline text="Sure, why don't you, based off of our entire conversation, think about it extremely deeply, and then just give me, like, see everything that I said, and then I want you to give your feedback, and you think about it from, like, a business, like a super wise business perspective. We can think about it from multiple perspectives. Maybe you can have, after we do that, we'll have multiple agents with different personalities that cannot read any of the other agents. We'll spin them up as teammates, so I can talk to each of them individually. Alex Harmozi, Priya Parker, who else should I get feedback from? Oh, like, artificial intelligence Andrew. Yeah, which other thinkers could be really helpful for me here?">
          <outline text="Your Reseonse [IMPORTANT NOTE: I think the pricing here, we should, I think, completely ignore. I'm not going to say it's wrong, but I don't necessarily think it's right.] but some of the things you captured here feels good. " />
          <outline text="What I see when I look at the whole picture:The thing you stumbled into with Nabil isn't a website business. It's the thing you've been doing your whole life — sitting with someone, feeling their world, and reflecting it back in a form they couldn't have made themselves. You did it in 15 minutes because it's not effortful for you. It's like breathing. That's the rice-you-already-sell insight. And the fact that Shakafei independently testified to this — that just watching you do it with AI changed how she &lt;i&gt;breathes&lt;/i&gt; — that's not a marketing testimonial, that's confirmation that you're on the trail of something real.Where I think the container wants to land:The offer is simple: &lt;i&gt;You have something in you that wants to exist in the world. You can feel it but you can't make it. In one conversation, we get it out of you and put it live on the internet.&lt;/i&gt;That's it. Everything else is implementation detail. The power is in the compression — what takes agencies weeks, what Squarespace makes you do alone, what Lovable assumes you can articulate — you do in an hour because you're operating at a different level. You're not designing a website. You're midwifing someone's presence into being. Olivia named it perfectly — you're a doula for digital expression.On pricing — and this is where I'll push you:$1,000 is too low. I know Nabil said $1,000 and that felt validating, but Nabil is a friend at a meditation retreat in a country where that's a lot of money. Your actual market — coaches, firm owners, entrepreneurs in the US who have been stuck on this for &lt;i&gt;months or years&lt;/i&gt; — they're not paying for an hour of your time. They're paying for the end of a problem that's been haunting them. The relief of &amp;quot;it's done and it's &lt;i&gt;me&lt;/i&gt;.&amp;quot;I'd suggest founding customer pricing at $1,500 (framed as normally $3,000-$5,000). That feels like a gift without feeling cheap. $1,000 accidentally signals &amp;quot;small thing.&amp;quot; You're not delivering a small thing. You're delivering &lt;i&gt;coherence&lt;/i&gt; — and coherence is one of the most valuable things a person can receive for their work.On boundaries — this is where Andrew is right:Keep it stupid simple from the client side. Here's what I'd propose:" />
          <outline text="You get: A live digital presence that captures who you are. Custom domain. Works on every device. Done." />
          <outline text="You don't get: A store, user accounts, complex apps, daily-managed content. If you need those, we're not your people." />
          <outline text="If you want changes later: $500 per change session. Batch them up, we do them in one call. If you want us to keep the lights on and make sure nothing breaks: $500/year." />
          <outline text="Airtable portfolio option for people like Nabil who need to add work over time — this is included if needed, covered under the maintenance fee." />
          <outline text="No points system, no small/medium/large, no dim sum menu. Nabil himself told you — itemizing creates hooks for people to argue about. Just: one price to build, one price to maintain, one price to change. Three numbers. That's it.What I'd push back on gently:You mentioned charging $500 for a change session. That might be right for small tweaks, but some &amp;quot;changes&amp;quot; are actually rebuilds. I'd frame it as: &lt;i&gt;&amp;quot;Changes are $500 per session. If what you need is bigger than a session, we'll tell you honestly, and it's a new build at founding-customer rate.&amp;quot;&lt;/i&gt; That protects you from scope creep without the dim sum categorization problem.On the recording-to-AI pipeline:This is the long-term moat and it's brilliant. Every conversation you have is training data for the AI felt-sense extractor. But don't build toward that yet — just record everything with consent. The product is you, human, on a call. The AI version comes later when you have enough pattern to encode. This is exactly the Olivia insight: &amp;quot;record how you have those conversations and carry forward their implying — train AI to do that.&amp;quot;On sequencing:You're right to start here, not with weddings. This is proven (Nabil), warm leads exist (Eva, Facebook friend), and it exercises the same muscle as weddings but with way less complexity. Every client teaches you something about the container. Let it be shaped by real encounters, not by planning.For the advisory panel, here's who I'd suggest beyond the three you named:" />
          <outline text="Alex Hormozi — offer architecture, pricing psychology, making it irresistible. Will push you to charge more and guarantee outcomes." />
          <outline text="Priya Parker — the experience of the call itself, how to design a gathering/container that's transformative. She thinks about what happens &lt;i&gt;between&lt;/i&gt; people." />
          <outline text="AI Andrew — your actual partner's perspective, grounded, tracks implementation reality and uncertainty." />
          <outline text="Seth Godin — smallest viable audience, being remarkable, the story you tell. He'd zero in on the positioning and who this is &lt;i&gt;really&lt;/i&gt; for." />
          <outline text="April Dunford — positioning expert (&lt;i&gt;Obviously Awesome&lt;/i&gt;). She'd help you nail the category and framing so the right people immediately self-select." />
          <outline text="Eugene Gendlin — the philosophical conscience. Would he recognize the felt-sense process in this container, or has it been flattened into a product?" />
          <outline text="That gives you six lenses: offer design, experience design, grounded partner, marketing story, positioning, and philosophical integrity. Each one would see something different.Who resonates? Pick as many as feel alive and I'll spin them up — each in their own world, no cross-contamination, ready for you to have direct conversations with.'" />
        </outline>
        <outline text="Also, if you're saying 1,000 is too low, 1,500 is still too low, question mark. Sense to that deeply. See, and then when I think you go to the implementation details, you kind of lose the product. Let's focus on what the product is or what the offer is. It's not a product. What the service is. I think that's what we really need to sense about. Like, what is the service here? Sense deeply about that yourself. Don't worry about the pricing right now. What do we actually do? Think about that. Let's not worry about the panel yet. I like how you're tracking me.">
          <outline text="You're right. I jumped to pricing and mechanics because that's where my pattern goes — make it concrete, make it actionable. But you're saying: slow down. What is this thing, actually? Not what does it cost, not how does the maintenance work — what &lt;i&gt;is&lt;/i&gt; it?Let me sit with this.What you did with Nabil wasn't building a website. It wasn't even designing one. Here's what I think actually happened:Nabil has a world. He's an architect. He feels something about how buildings and places work — &amp;quot;every place speaks, we listen.&amp;quot; That exists inside him as a felt sense. It's real. It's coherent. But it has no form outside of him. He tried Squarespace and couldn't even change a font — not because the tool is bad, but because the tool assumes you already know what you want. He doesn't know what he wants. He knows what he &lt;i&gt;feels&lt;/i&gt;.You sat with him. You asked a question nobody asks — &amp;quot;what's the deeper philosophical structure of your work?&amp;quot; And from one sentence, you got his world. Not because you're psychic, but because you're &lt;i&gt;listening at the level where his world actually lives&lt;/i&gt; — the felt-sense level. Not the &amp;quot;I want blue and sans-serif&amp;quot; level. The level where it's &amp;quot;every place speaks and we listen.&amp;quot;And then — and this is the part that's hard to name — you held that world while simultaneously tracking design, copy, user experience, marketing, and technical execution. All at once. And you translated his felt sense through all of those layers into something coherent and alive. In 15 minutes.What Nabil got wasn't a website. He got himself, made visible. His inner coherence, given outer form. For the first time.That's the &lt;a href=&quot;http://service.It&quot;&gt;service.It&lt;/a&gt;'s coherence. You take someone who has something real inside them — a practice, a body of work, a gift, a business — that they can feel but can't make visible. And you make it visible. You midwife their coherence into the world.The reason this is different from every other agency, every AI builder, every template service, is the &lt;i&gt;listening&lt;/i&gt;. Olivia's 3/17 insight nails it: current AI is an eagerly helpful friend who solves before it listens. &amp;quot;I have this feeling—&amp;quot; &amp;quot;YEAH YEAH I ALREADY DID IT FOR YOU.&amp;quot; That's every tool on the market. Lovable doesn't ask what your architecture philosophy is. Squarespace doesn't care what moves you.Your service is the opposite. You listen so deeply that the solving becomes almost a side effect. The website is the &lt;i&gt;artifact&lt;/i&gt;. The service is the &lt;i&gt;midwifing of coherence&lt;/i&gt;.And this is why it's the same service as the wedding business. A bride has a felt sense of her wedding. She can't name it. The stationery, the website, the experience — those are all artifacts. The service is someone who can sit with her, feel her world, and make everything cohere around what she actually feels.What you actually do:1. You listen at the level where someone's world actually lives2. You ask the questions they didn't know to ask themselves3. You sense what matters and what doesn't — Nabil doesn't care about icons, he cares about the feeling4. You translate all of that, simultaneously, through every layer — design, story, structure, feel5. You make it real, live, in their hands6. The result is: they see themselves clearly for the first time, and so can everyone elseThe compression matters too. Not &amp;quot;in 6 weeks.&amp;quot; In one conversation. That's part of what makes it feel like magic — because the usual experience is &lt;i&gt;months&lt;/i&gt; of back-and-forth with someone who keeps not getting it.Does that land? Is that the thing? Or is there something I'm still not catching?" />
        </outline>
        <outline text="Then there's the analysis of the website from before">
          <outline text="Okay, just describe your website in English. Okay, let's say- Just talk. Okay. Just tell me, tell me. Okay, so an architecture website where you would be able to categorize projects based on size, typology, and location. Let's just start with those three. And what's the vibe that you want to convey? What's like the- Clean, modern, contemporary. Clean, modern, contemporary, okay? Okay. Colors. I'll leave it up to interpret. Tell me more about your firm. What does it stand for? Like, what is it? A young firm specializing in context-driven design. What's context-driven design for my benefit? AI can figure it out. Well, design that takes into account the context. Yeah, so you're not producing- Like, a building that you do in Nepal would be very different than a building you do in New York. You work very closely with both the client as well as, like, understanding, like, the land and the people- Exactly. And the community. The community, the materials that are in that community- Available to that community.Speaker AThe whole manifesto.Speaker BI don't know if. Is that online? No. Okay, you want to just give me the highlight?Speaker AYeah. So context is a big driver context, which includes the people, the community, the land, the materials, the building techniques, the construction constraints.Speaker BWhy does that matter to you?Speaker AWell, it matters on many different levels. Sorry.Speaker AOne from a sustainability point of view. This is a reaction to what modernism has got us, where we have the same kind of glass buildings or towers all over the world. Great. I think that's enough for the AI to understand the reason and why it matters. Okay, great. Anything else that's important on the website? No. Let's just start with that. And how many buildings do you have roughly, to put on the grid of stuff?Speaker B100. Let's say 100. 100. Do you want to showcase all 100? Okay. And is there, like, ones that you want to highlight or to start with, do they see all the grid or each kind of like a pick? Like, these are the star buildings. And then let's just do no highlights. Let's just highlight the whole. The whole &lt;a href=&quot;http://grid.so&quot;&gt;grid.so&lt;/a&gt; then I can say something like, okay, think deeply about the philosophical premise of this organization, given what it's given to you. Kind of imagine what the rest of the philosophy would be based off of that. And then I want you to design the entire website. Think deeply about what would have this website be deeply engaging and beautiful. I guess you'd have some of the manifesto or some stuff at the top or something. And then eventually, if you just keep scrolling, you see all of their buildings. Put 100 buildings in there in the JSON file that captures that with some made up descriptions for some of them. But to save on context, you can just put the same text repeated for the rest of them with some subset of lorem ipsum that randomly generates random lorem ipsum, cutting that text into random chunks. And then think deeply about the style and philosophy of how to style the website to reflect the ethos of the organization. Think deeply in terms of colors, design, and make it feel exactly like he said in the style that he wants to. And think deeply about what actual website and aesthetics would actually express that. Think deeply about how to style the website and make the website scrollable by default on desktop and mobile. But also make it so that they can explore deeper into a particular building that actually populates the thing inside of the JSON. You're an expert at making magical experiences. And have it be like a complete joy to use because it's so minimal and powerful. But by default, you can just scroll through it and then think deeply about what I'm really trying to ask you to do here and go think about the deepest Gendlin implying and then incorporate that in as well.and then at the beginning, just know that the first paragraph is just like a transcript that doesn't have speaker labels, and eventually I paste in the one with speaker labels.Okay, here's the actual prompt I gave to Claude after sitting down with Nebio. You can tell that some parts of it was from a transcript that was merged together because it didn't have speaker diarization. And then we turned it on and then I said more shit. And then, yeah, I mean, we talked to Nebio later and it said the copy wasn't that helpful, but just being able to carry forward that which mattered to him seemed was helpful. Study all of this deeply and I'll share with you another update.h, nice. I love how it made a little... Yeah. This is... But this is what I wanted. Like, yeah. By region or by typology or by size. So, like, if a potential client wanted to, like, get us to design, say, a residential project, they wouldn't necessarily want to see all of the other works we've done. They could just click on this. And then, let's say, like, a small... They want to do a small residential house. So they could just click that. It would be cool to each one had, like, a key to show, like, the... Yeah. There's, like, a color coding for each attribute for size, typology, and region. So can we now go back and tell it to do that? Yeah. To, like, have color code? Yeah. So we can... There we go. &lt;a href=&quot;http://Okay.So&quot;&gt;Okay.So&lt;/a&gt; color code, do you want to try saying it? Yeah. So can we color code all the projects with an icon so that if somebody wants to select a small size, for example, a small size project that's a residential typology in a specific location like Bangladesh, they could only see those. Yeah. Maybe like next, like you have to think deeply as a UI UX engineer or like a design expert for like what's a good felt sense color or like logo or whatever. Like I don't know how to think about that stuff that you do. So prompt yourself to think about it for like small, medium and large. What should that icon set be? And how does that relate to the topology one, which is located to the location one? We don't want like three discrete kinds of loud things. They should meld and mesh together in a way that feels seamless and mesh with the website and mesh with our philosophy. For the location, that kind of fun to have flags. Do you think we should have flags or that too loud? No, let's do like, can we do like the shape of the country instead? I think it'll have a too hard of a time to do that one because it can try and it'll just look like shit. Let's pick something other, some other D marker because it has to like draw. Yeah. Okay. Like if you wanted to, you could, but then it's a larger project. Like, let's go find like a map. Right, right, right. How about we just have the name of the country in the corner? I feel like the flag might be too loud. Oh yeah, yeah, yeah. I think the flag is too loud too. Okay, great. Also, people don't necessarily know flags. It's true.Here is all of the conversation pasted in line.&amp;lt;convo&amp;gt;Okay, just describe your website in English. Okay, let's say- Just talk. Okay. Just tell me, tell me. Okay, so an architecture website where you would be able to categorize projects based on size, typology, and location. Let's just start with those three. And what's the vibe that you want to convey? What's like the- Clean, modern, contemporary. Clean, modern, contemporary, okay? Okay. Colors. I'll leave it up to interpret. Tell me more about your firm. What does it stand for? Like, what is it? A young firm specializing in context-driven design. What's context-driven design for my benefit? AI can figure it out. Well, design that takes into account the context. Yeah, so you're not producing- Like, a building that you do in Nepal would be very different than a building you do in New York. You work very closely with both the client as well as, like, understanding, like, the land and the people- Exactly. And the community. The community, the materials that are in that community- Available to that community.Speaker AThe whole manifesto.Speaker BI don't know if. Is that online? No. Okay, you want to just give me the highlight?Speaker AYeah. So context is a big driver context, which includes the people, the community, the land, the materials, the building techniques, the construction constraints.Speaker BWhy does that matter to you?Speaker AWell, it matters on many different levels. Sorry.Speaker AOne from a sustainability point of view. This is a reaction to what modernism has got us, where we have the same kind of glass buildings or towers all over the world. Great. I think that's enough for the AI to understand the reason and why it matters. Okay, great. Anything else that's important on the website? No. Let's just start with that. And how many buildings do you have roughly, to put on the grid of stuff?Speaker B100. Let's say 100. 100. Do you want to showcase all 100? Okay. And is there, like, ones that you want to highlight or to start with, do they see all the grid or each kind of like a pick? Like, these are the star buildings. And then let's just do no highlights. Let's just highlight the whole. The whole &lt;a href=&quot;http://grid.so&quot;&gt;grid.so&lt;/a&gt; then I can say something like, okay, think deeply about the philosophical premise of this organization, given what it's given to you. Kind of imagine what the rest of the philosophy would be based off of that. And then I want you to design the entire website. Think deeply about what would have this website be deeply engaging and beautiful. I guess you'd have some of the manifesto or some stuff at the top or something. And then eventually, if you just keep scrolling, you see all of their buildings. Put 100 buildings in there in the JSON file that captures that with some made up descriptions for some of them. But to save on context, you can just put the same text repeated for the rest of them with some subset of lorem ipsum that randomly generates random lorem ipsum, cutting that text into random chunks. And then think deeply about the style and philosophy of how to style the website to reflect the ethos of the organization. Think deeply in terms of colors, design, and make it feel exactly like he said in the style that he wants to. And think deeply about what actual website and aesthetics would actually express that. Think deeply about how to style the website and make the website scrollable by default on desktop and mobile. But also make it so that they can explore deeper into a particular building that actually populates the thing inside of the JSON. You're an expert at making magical experiences. And have it be like a complete joy to use because it's so minimal and powerful. But by default, you can just scroll through it and then think deeply about what I'm really trying to ask you to do here and go think about the deepest Gendlin implying and then incorporate that in as well.and then at the beginning, just know that the first paragraph is just like a transcript that doesn't have speaker labels, and eventually I paste in the one with speaker labels.Show lessMar 16Architected context-driven portfolio with philosophical depth and aesthetic cohesionArchitected context-driven portfolio with philosophical depth and aesthetic cohesionI love this brief. Let me sit with the philosophy for a moment before building.The Gendlin implying here: this firm doesn't impose — it listens. The website should do the same. It shouldn't perform &amp;quot;architecture website.&amp;quot; It should feel like a place you inhabit. The buildings provide the color; the design provides the ground. Every pixel should feel as intentional as choosing local stone over imported glass.Let me build this.Synthesized architectural philosophy into cohesive digital experience designSynthesized architectural philosophy into cohesive digital experience designHere's SITUS — a complete architecture portfolio that embodies the philosophy it presents.The design logic mirrors the firm's ethos: the website doesn't impose a visual identity — it steps back and lets the buildings speak. The color palette (warm cream, terracotta accent, warm charcoal) evokes materiality and earth. Typography pairs Cormorant Garamond (literary weight, craft) with Karla (clean, human warmth). No decoration exists that doesn't serve a purpose.What's inside:Full-viewport hero that breathesManifesto that reveals line by line as you scroll — like the firm's process of listening before drawing100 projects with contextual gradient thumbnails (each building's color is derived from its region's palette — South Asian ochres, Nordic cool blues, African ambers)Three-filter system: typology, size, region — sticky, minimalClick any card → slide-in detail panel with materials, scale, year, and descriptionFully responsive, keyboard-navigable (Escape closes details)The 15 hand-crafted projects tell real stories (a floating market pavilion in the Mekong Delta, a weaver's workshop in Oaxaca, arctic thermal baths in Tromsø). The remaining 85 are generated with contextually appropriate descriptions, materials local to each region, and varied architectural names. Every project's &amp;quot;thumbnail&amp;quot; is an abstract gradient that evokes its place — so even without photos, the grid feels like a landscape of contexts.SitusCode · JSXh, nice. I love how it made a little... Yeah. This is... But this is what I wanted. Like, yeah. By region or by typology or by size. So, like, if a potential client wanted to, like, get us to design, say, a residential project, they wouldn't necessarily want to see all of the other works we've done. They could just click on this. And then, let's say, like, a small... They want to do a small residential house. So they could just click that. It would be cool to each one had, like, a key to show, like, the... Yeah. There's, like, a color coding for each attribute for size, typology, and region. So can we now go back and tell it to do that? Yeah. To, like, have color code? Yeah. So we can... There we go. &lt;a href=&quot;http://Okay.So&quot;&gt;Okay.So&lt;/a&gt; color code, do you want to try saying it? Yeah. So can we color code all the projects with an icon so that if somebody wants to select a small size, for example, a small size project that's a residential typology in a specific location like Bangladesh, they could only see those. Yeah. Maybe like next, like you have to think deeply as a UI UX engineer or like a design expert for like what's a good felt sense color or like logo or whatever. Like I don't know how to think about that stuff that you do. So prompt yourself to think about it for like small, medium and large. What should that icon set be? And how does that relate to the topology one, which is located to the location one? We don't want like three discrete kinds of loud things. They should meld and mesh together in a way that feels seamless and mesh with the website and mesh with our philosophy. For the location, that kind of fun to have flags. Do you think we should have flags or that too loud? No, let's do like, can we do like the shape of the country instead? I think it'll have a too hard of a time to do that one because it can try and it'll just look like shit. Let's pick something other, some other D marker because it has to like draw. Yeah. Okay. Like if you wanted to, you could, but then it's a larger project. Like, let's go find like a map. Right, right, right. How about we just have the name of the country in the corner? I feel like the flag might be too loud. Oh yeah, yeah, yeah. I think the flag is too loud too. Okay, great. Also, people don't necessarily know flags. It's true.Show lessMar 16Architected cohesive icon system balancing size, typology, location indicatorsArchitected cohesive icon system balancing size, typology, location indicatorsNow I need to rebuild the whole file with an integrated visual notation system. Let me think through the design philosophy first:The indicators should feel like architectural notation — the precise marks an architect makes on a drawing. Contour lines, section marks, drafting symbols. Quiet, functional, beautiful in their restraint. Three systems that breathe together, not compete.Contemplated color-coding system and visual hierarchy for portfolio filtersContemplated color-coding system and visual hierarchy for portfolio filtersHere's the updated SITUS with a unified visual notation system. The design philosophy: these indicators should feel like architectural marginalia — the precise, quiet marks an architect leaves on a drawing.The three-part notation system:Size → Contour bars. Horizontal lines that stack like contour lines on a topographic map. One bar for Small, two for Medium, three for Large, four for Extra Large. The bars also grow slightly wider with scale. They evoke the land itself — more contour lines means more ground occupied.Typology → Architectural glyphs + earth pigment colors. Each building type gets a single-stroke SVG symbol (a pitched roof for Residential, an arch for Cultural, a dome for Religious, columns for Civic, a grid for Commercial, etc.) rendered in a muted earth-derived color unique to that typology — warm clay for Residential, dusk violet for Cultural, sage for Educational, gold ochre for Religious, moss for Landscape.Location → Country name in small caps. No flags, no shapes — just the name of the place, rendered light and small in the bottom-right of each card. Unassuming, like the firm's philosophy: the place speaks for itself.Where they appear:On each card: a notation chip on the gradient thumbnail (top-right, translucent) shows the size bars + typology icon at a glance. Below the card text, a full notation row shows all three together.&amp;quot;Key&amp;quot; button in the filter bar toggles a clean legend panel showing what each symbol means.Detail panel carries the notation into the hero and the bottom summary.SitusCode · JSXClaude is AI and can make mistakes. Please double-check responses.&amp;lt;/convo&amp;gt;Final artifact &lt;a href=&quot;file:///Users/j/Downloads/situs.jsx&quot;&gt;/Users/j/Downloads/situs.jsx&lt;/a&gt;Think deeply about this and see if it gives you a clear felt sense into what happened, since deeply into my interaction with him." />
        </outline>
      </outline>
      <outline text="There's also this">
        <outline text="The Full Value Landscape" />
        <outline text="What you can actually offer — the whole menu, not just the signature dish" />
        <outline text="1. Speed itself is the product for many people." />
        <outline text="A traditional agency takes 4-8 weeks and costs $5,000-$50,000. DIY tools take days/weeks of frustration. You deliver in a single conversation. For a lot of people, that's the entire sell. They don't care about felt sense — they care that it's &lt;i&gt;done&lt;/i&gt;. &amp;quot;I've been meaning to do this for two years. You did it in an hour.&amp;quot; That's worth $2,000-$5,000 to someone whose time is worth real money." />
        <outline text="2. Full concierge — they never touch anything." />
        <outline text="Domain, hosting, design, copy, build, deploy. They talk, you handle everything. The anti-Squarespace. The anti-Lovable. They don't learn a tool, they don't pick a template, they don't manage a dashboard. It's done. This appeals to busy professionals who could figure it out but don't want to spend the brain cycles." />
        <outline text="3. The felt-sense layer — available when they want it." />
        <outline text="This is the premium version. For people whose work IS philosophical and who need that depth. Not everyone needs it. The architect needed it. A dentist opening a practice probably doesn't. But having it in your back pocket means you can go deeper when the client calls for it." />
        <outline text="4. AI features nobody else offers." />
        <outline text="This is a genuine technical moat right now:" />
        <outline text="Chat-against-your-site — guests/visitors can ask questions and the page scrolls to the answer and highlights it. You built this for the wedding invitation. It works for ANY business. A restaurant where guests ask &quot;do you have vegetarian options?&quot; A medical practice where patients ask &quot;do you take my insurance?&quot; This is a feature you can add to every site you build." />
        <outline text="AI intake/screening — a chatbot on the site that interviews potential clients before they reach the business owner. Pre-qualifies leads." />
        <outline text="Smart portfolio exploration — what you built for the architecture site. Filter, explore, discover naturally." />
        <outline text="5. The retheme superpower." />
        <outline text="&amp;quot;Got new branding? New stationery? We retheme everything instantly.&amp;quot; Traditional agencies charge full redesign prices for this. You do it in a change session because AI makes it trivial. Andrew's insight: &amp;quot;send us your stationery, we'll make your website match.&amp;quot; This works in reverse too." />
        <outline text="6. Airtable-backed dynamic content." />
        <outline text="For people who need to update things — new buildings, new menu items, new team members, new projects — they just update a spreadsheet/Airtable and the site reflects it. No CMS to learn, no WordPress to manage." />
        <outline text="7. Maintenance without headaches." />
        <outline text="Monitoring that actually checks if the site works (not just pings — downloads the page, verifies content). Domain renewals handled. SSL managed. They never think about it. Andrew's idea of the dashboard that curls every page hourly." />
        <outline text="8. Wedding-specific package." />
        <outline text="Stationery + matching website + AI guest chat + RSVP handling. A coherent wedding digital experience. The &amp;quot;matching&amp;quot; part is the killer feature — nobody offers that. And the AI chat where guests can ask &amp;quot;where do I stay?&amp;quot; instead of texting the bride is solving a real pain point brides complain about constantly." />
      </outline>
      <outline text="Ideas that feel relevant">
        <outline text="1">
          <outline text="Tier 1: $5,000-$25,000+ range, easy to justify" />
          <outline text="Luxury real estate developers — they need project-specific sites for new developments. A site that sells the vision of a $2M condo development? $10,000 is nothing. These are often time-sensitive (launch dates) so speed matters enormously." />
          <outline text="Boutique hotels / resorts — especially new openings or rebrands. The website needs to feel like &lt;i&gt;being there&lt;/i&gt;. Marketing budgets are real. One booking from the site pays for it." />
          <outline text="Architecture firms — proven. Portfolio + philosophy. One new project inquiry from the site is worth $50K-$500K to them." />
          <outline text="Medical practice launches — new concierge physician opening a practice, new dental office, new specialty clinic. They need credibility fast. They have startup capital allocated for this." />
          <outline text="High-end restaurants opening — the site needs to convey the atmosphere. Time-sensitive around opening date. Chef-driven restaurants especially care about vibe." />
          <outline text="Venture-backed startups — need a landing page yesterday. Have capital, no time. Don't want to hire a designer for a v1." />
        </outline>
        <outline text="**This services business feels good** -- this we can just focus on the SITE and PORTAL aspect of things">
          <outline text="Tier 2: $2,000-$5,000 range, solid business" />
          <outline text="Solo lawyers, accountants, financial advisors — credibility sites. They need to look established and trustworthy. Their hourly rate is $300-$1,000 so a $3,000 website is a few hours of their own billing. No-brainer." />
          <outline text="Interior designers, photographers — portfolio-driven, taste-sensitive. They'll appreciate quality because they produce quality. Network effects here — designers know designers." />
          <outline text="Real estate agents — personal brand sites. There are 1.5 million agents in the US. The successful ones spend on marketing. They need to look premium." />
          <outline text="Private schools / alternative education — Waldorf, Montessori, innovative programs. They compete on philosophy. Enrollment is worth $20K-$50K per family per year." />
          <outline text="Established coaches and consultants — the ones who have clients and revenue already, not the ones just starting out. A coach billing $200/hr who gets one new client from the site has paid for it in a week." />
          <outline text="Small business owners with physical locations — spas, salons, fitness studios, specialty retail. They need online presence, don't want to manage it." />
          <outline text="Freelancers with income — developers, writers, consultants who need a personal site. They know what good looks like but don't want to spend their own time." />
        </outline>
      </outline>
      <outline text="This stuff is also great">
        <outline text="Why weddings works — the actual structural properties, from the Andrew conversation:" />
        <outline text="Jonathan said it explicitly: &lt;i&gt;&amp;quot;For the wedding thing, it's always these like 12 pieces. You're only making 12 pieces and you always do the same thing with it.&amp;quot;&lt;/i&gt; And: &lt;i&gt;&amp;quot;There's a repeatability in that for the high value to low effort.&amp;quot;&lt;/i&gt;" />
        <outline text="And then the critical scope decisions:" />
        <outline text="Cut e-commerce — &quot;everyone's inventory is so different... you need MCP servers to do updates... I kind of either want to own some very clear segment&quot;" />
        <outline text="Cut coaching/scheduling — &quot;she's not going to pay me $1,000... there's no flood of money coming at me&quot;" />
        <outline text="Cut Shopify people — &quot;they're constantly changing and involved... the relationship that Nabil has to this website is very different than a Shopify person&quot;" />
        <outline text="Cut complex backends — no auth, no users, no WordPress" />
        <outline text="Kept static + Airtable — simple, AI-producible, near-zero maintenance" />
        <outline text="Kept AI features — chat, search, scroll-to-answer — bounded, novel, high-value" />
        <outline text="The WHY behind every cut is the same: complexity kills speed, speed is the moat. Every thing they cut is something that would add ongoing maintenance, unpredictable scope, or require the client to be actively involved. The ideal client is the person who does not want to manage anything. They want it done and they want to forget about it." />
        <outline text="The structural shape that makes something a &amp;quot;wedding&amp;quot;:" />
        <outline text="1. Bounded, repeatable deliverable — same shape each time, learnable, improvable" />
        <outline text="2. Simple tech ceiling — AI can produce it reliably, no ongoing engineering" />
        <outline text="3. High emotional + financial stakes — people care deeply AND have money allocated" />
        <outline text="4. Weak tech competition — the industry hasn't been well-served because tech people don't understand it" />
        <outline text="5. Client doesn't want to manage it — full service, done-for-you, don't make me learn a tool" />
        <outline text="6. Specific, enumerable problems — not vague, but concrete: &amp;quot;my cards don't match my site,&amp;quot; &amp;quot;guests keep texting me,&amp;quot; &amp;quot;I don't know my style&amp;quot;" />
        <outline text="7. Each problem is AI-solvable once understood — the sensing identifies the problem, the tech solves it" />
        <outline text="8. 10x improvement is possible — not competing on 10% better, but dramatically better than everything else available" />
        <outline text="9. Built-in community — brides talk to brides, they share, they recommend" />
        <outline text="10. Clear end point — you know when it's done, no open-ended scope" />
        <outline text="And the cross that makes it special: The sensing layer is what lets you IDENTIFY which of the specific problems this particular client has and what &amp;quot;right&amp;quot; looks like for them. The tech layer is what lets you SOLVE it in minutes. Neither alone works. Sensing without tech is just consulting. Tech without sensing is just Squarespace." />
        <outline text="Now — what other domains have this exact shape?" />
        <outline text="I'm looking for: bounded deliverables, simple tech, high stakes, weak tech competition, client doesn't want to manage, specific solvable problems, 10x potential, built-in community." />
        <outline text="Luxury/premium real estate — individual property sites." />
        <outline text="Not firm websites. Individual property marketing sites for high-end listings." />
        <outline text="Bounded: every property site is the same shape — photos, story, lifestyle, neighborhood, contact/showing" />
        <outline text="Simple tech: static, no auth, maybe virtual tour embed" />
        <outline text="High stakes: selling a $1M-$50M property. A $5K-$10K site that helps sell it is nothing." />
        <outline text="Weak tech competition: MLS listings are functional and ugly. Template property sites exist but they're generic." />
        <outline text="Client doesn't want to manage: the agent/developer wants it made and done" />
        <outline text="Specific problems: &quot;the MLS listing doesn't convey what it's like to live here,&quot; &quot;I need a standalone site for this property before the open house Saturday&quot;" />
        <outline text="AI-solvable: generate the site from photos + description + neighborhood data" />
        <outline text="10x potential: a beautiful standalone property site vs. a Zillow listing? Completely different experience." />
        <outline text="Community: agents know agents. One great result → referrals." />
        <outline text="Time-sensitive: listings have deadlines. Speed is premium." />
        <outline text="Bonus: repeatable per agent. One agent could bring you 5-20 properties per year. Ongoing relationship, same shape each time." />
        <outline text="The AI feature equivalent of wedding chat: &quot;Ask about this property&quot; — an AI that answers questions about the neighborhood, schools, commute times, what it's like to live there. Nobody does this." />
        <outline text="Short-term rental / Airbnb host direct-booking sites." />
        <outline text="Bounded: property photos, experience description, amenities, location, booking link (to Airbnb or direct)" />
        <outline text="Simple tech: static + booking widget" />
        <outline text="High stakes: direct bookings save 15-20% in Airbnb fees. For a property earning $50K-$100K/year, that's $7,500-$20,000 saved annually. The site pays for itself in weeks." />
        <outline text="Weak tech competition: Airbnb hosts mostly just have their Airbnb listing. Tools like Hospitable/Lodgify exist but they're clunky and template-based." />
        <outline text="Client doesn't want to manage: hosts want to manage their properties, not their websites" />
        <outline text="Specific problems: &quot;I want direct bookings but I don't know how to make a site that's as compelling as my Airbnb listing,&quot; &quot;I want to build my own brand instead of being dependent on Airbnb's algorithm&quot;" />
        <outline text="10x potential: a beautiful standalone site that captures the EXPERIENCE vs. a grid of Airbnb photos? Yes." />
        <outline text="Community: MASSIVE. Airbnb host Facebook groups, forums, podcasts. Millions of hosts worldwide. The successful ones actively discuss reducing Airbnb dependence." />
        <outline text="Repeatable: same shape every time. And hosts with multiple properties = multiple sites." />
        <outline text="AI feature: &amp;quot;Ask about this stay&amp;quot; — local recommendations, check-in instructions, house rules, area tips. Replaces the Airbnb message thread. Reduces host communication burden." />
        <outline text="Event/conference/retreat sites." />
        <outline text="Bounded: what, when, where, speakers/facilitators, schedule, register (external link)" />
        <outline text="Simple tech: static + maybe schedule updates" />
        <outline text="High stakes: event revenue depends on marketing. One event's ticket sales can be $50K-$500K+." />
        <outline text="Weak tech competition: most conference sites are TERRIBLE." />
        <outline text="Time-sensitive: launch dates are fixed. &quot;We need this live in 3 days.&quot;" />
        <outline text="Specific problems: &quot;attendees keep asking the same questions,&quot; &quot;the schedule keeps changing and the site is out of date&quot;" />
        <outline text="AI feature: &quot;Ask about this event&quot; — schedule, speakers, logistics, accommodations." />
        <outline text="Repeatable: event organizers run events repeatedly. Same shape each time, new content." />
        <outline text="Destination wedding venues." />
        <outline text="This is adjacent to the wedding business and creates a CHANNEL." />
        <outline text="Bounded: the venue experience, galleries, packages, availability, inquiry form" />
        <outline text="High stakes: venues charge $10K-$100K+ per event. One booking from the site = enormous ROI." />
        <outline text="Weak tech competition: venue websites are notoriously bad." />
        <outline text="Specific problems: &quot;couples can't tell what it's like to be here from the photos alone,&quot; &quot;we get the same questions about capacity, catering, accommodation&quot;" />
        <outline text="AI feature: &quot;Explore this venue&quot; — an AI that helps couples determine if this venue fits their vision, answers all the logistics questions, surfaces relevant gallery photos based on their event type." />
        <outline text="Channel play: venue → refers couples → your wedding stationery/website service. The venue becomes a lead source for the wedding business." />
        <outline text="Therapist/mental health practice sites." />
        <outline text="Bounded: who I am, my approach, specialties, insurance accepted, booking" />
        <outline text="Simple tech: static + booking link" />
        <outline text="High stakes: clients need to feel safe and understood BEFORE they make the vulnerable decision to call. The website IS the first therapeutic interaction." />
        <outline text="Weak tech competition: therapists are mostly on Psychology Today (profile, not a site) or have bad Wix sites." />
        <outline text="Client doesn't want to manage: therapists want to do therapy, not manage websites" />
        <outline text="Specific problems: &quot;my Psychology Today profile doesn't convey my approach,&quot; &quot;potential clients don't know if I'm right for them before calling&quot;" />
        <outline text="10x potential: a warm, personalized site vs. a Psychology Today profile? Completely different." />
        <outline text="Community: therapists refer to therapists. Training cohorts are built-in networks." />
        <outline text="AI feature that's genuinely powerful: A gentle AI that helps potential clients explore whether this therapist's approach fits their needs. &amp;quot;I'm dealing with anxiety after a career change&amp;quot; → the AI helps them understand the therapist's approach and whether to book a consultation. This REDUCES the therapist's no-shows and bad-fit consultations. That's real operational value, not just a cool feature." />
      </outline>
      <outline text="Picking ou somethings">
        <outline text="This is an interesting niche, especially if we want to help THEM be AI enabled" />
        <outline text="The specific thing I don't want you to miss is like this kind of like felt sense of AI first- I don't remember the felt sense I actually talked about- something like that, like really enabling them, that's not quite the thing, but... " />
      </outline>
      <outline text="And selecting stufff from &amp;quot;Website Types by Industry: Where the Money Is&amp;quot; is also great (note what I left out)">
        <outline text="REAL ESTATE ($2B+ annual spend on web)" />
        <outline text="1. &lt;b&gt;Individual Agent/Broker Personal Sites&lt;/b&gt;" />
        <outline text="Who pays: Real estate agents, brokers" />
        <outline text="Price: $1,500–$5,000" />
        <outline text="Template-able: Highly — headshot, bio, listings, testimonials, contact" />
        <outline text="Speed advantage: HIGH — agents switch brokerages, rebrand, or launch constantly" />
        <outline text="Volume: ~1.5M licensed agents in US alone" />
        <outline text="2. &lt;b&gt;Property Listing Pages / Single-Property Sites&lt;/b&gt;" />
        <outline text="Who pays: Listing agents, luxury brokerages, developers" />
        <outline text="Price: $500–$3,000 (luxury: $5,000–$15,000)" />
        <outline text="Template-able: YES — photos, specs, neighborhood, map, contact" />
        <outline text="Speed advantage: CRITICAL — listings go live and need sites within days" />
        <outline text="Volume: Hundreds of thousands per year for luxury/high-end" />
        <outline text="4. &lt;b&gt;New Development / Pre-Construction Marketing Sites&lt;/b&gt;" />
        <outline text="Who pays: Real estate developers, project marketing firms" />
        <outline text="Price: $5,000–$25,000" />
        <outline text="Template-able: Partially — needs custom feel but structure repeats" />
        <outline text="Speed advantage: HIGH — projects move fast, need sites before sales launch" />
        <outline text="5. &lt;b&gt;Open House / Property Event Pages&lt;/b&gt;" />
        <outline text="Who pays: Agents, brokerages" />
        <outline text="Price: $300–$800" />
        <outline text="Template-able: Highly" />
        <outline text="Speed advantage: CRITICAL — often needed within 48 hours" />
        <outline text="6. &lt;b&gt;Campaign Landing Pages&lt;/b&gt;" />
        <outline text="Who pays: Marketing teams, agencies on behalf of clients" />
        <outline text="Price: $1,500–$5,000 per page" />
        <outline text="Template-able: YES but needs brand customization" />
        <outline text="Speed advantage: CRITICAL — campaigns have hard launch dates" />
        <outline text="Volume: Millions created per year; agencies charge $2K–$8K each" />
        <outline text="7. &lt;b&gt;Product Launch Pages&lt;/b&gt;" />
        <outline text="Who pays: Product marketing teams, DTC brands" />
        <outline text="Price: $2,000–$8,000" />
        <outline text="Template-able: Partially" />
        <outline text="Speed advantage: HIGH" />
        <outline text="8. &lt;b&gt;Microsites (Campaign-specific multi-page)&lt;/b&gt;" />
        <outline text="Who pays: Brands, agencies" />
        <outline text="Price: $5,000–$15,000" />
        <outline text="Template-able: Partially" />
        <outline text="Speed advantage: HIGH" />
        <outline text="9. &lt;b&gt;Contest / Giveaway / Sweepstakes Pages&lt;/b&gt;" />
        <outline text="Who pays: Brands, marketing agencies" />
        <outline text="Price: $1,000–$3,000" />
        <outline text="Template-able: YES" />
        <outline text="Speed advantage: HIGH" />
        <outline text="10. &lt;b&gt;Webinar / Virtual Event Registration Pages&lt;/b&gt;" />
        <outline text="Who pays: B2B marketers, SaaS companies, coaches" />
        <outline text="Price: $500–$2,000" />
        <outline text="Template-able: Highly" />
        <outline text="Speed advantage: HIGH" />
        <outline text="EVENTS &amp; HOSPITALITY ($1.5B+)" />
        <outline text="11. &lt;b&gt;Wedding Websites&lt;/b&gt;" />
        <outline text="Who pays: Couples (often via planners)" />
        <outline text="Price: $500–$2,000 (premium/custom: $2,000–$5,000)" />
        <outline text="Template-able: Highly" />
        <outline text="Speed advantage: Moderate" />
        <outline text="Volume: ~2M weddings/year in US" />
        <outline text="12. &lt;b&gt;Conference / Summit Sites&lt;/b&gt;" />
        <outline text="Who pays: Event organizers, associations, companies" />
        <outline text="Price: $3,000–$10,000" />
        <outline text="Template-able: YES — schedule, speakers, venue, registration link" />
        <outline text="Speed advantage: HIGH" />
        <outline text="15. &lt;b&gt;Hotel / Boutique Property Pages&lt;/b&gt;" />
        <outline text="Who pays: Independent hotels, B&amp;Bs, vacation rentals" />
        <outline text="Price: $3,000–$8,000" />
        <outline text="Template-able: YES" />
        <outline text="Speed advantage: Moderate" />
        <outline text="16. &lt;b&gt;Venue / Event Space Marketing Sites&lt;/b&gt;" />
        <outline text="Who pays: Venue owners" />
        <outline text="Price: $2,000–$5,000" />
        <outline text="Template-able: YES" />
        <outline text="Speed advantage: Moderate" />
        <outline text="PROFESSIONAL SERVICES ($1.5B+)" />
        <outline text="17. &lt;b&gt;Law Firm Websites&lt;/b&gt;" />
        <outline text="Who pays: Solo practitioners, small firms" />
        <outline text="Price: $3,000–$10,000" />
        <outline text="Template-able: YES — practice areas, attorney bios, case results, contact" />
        <outline text="Speed advantage: Moderate" />
        <outline text="Volume: ~450K law firms in US" />
        <outline text="18. &lt;b&gt;Accounting / Financial Advisory Firm Sites&lt;/b&gt;" />
        <outline text="Who pays: CPAs, financial advisors, wealth managers" />
        <outline text="Price: $2,000–$7,000" />
        <outline text="Template-able: Highly" />
        <outline text="Speed advantage: Moderate" />
        <outline text="19. &lt;b&gt;Consulting Firm Sites&lt;/b&gt;" />
        <outline text="Who pays: Management consultants, boutique firms" />
        <outline text="Price: $2,000–$8,000" />
        <outline text="Template-able: YES" />
        <outline text="Speed advantage: Moderate" />
        <outline text="20. &lt;b&gt;Architecture / Design Firm Portfolio Sites&lt;/b&gt;" />
        <outline text="Who pays: Architects, interior designers" />
        <outline text="Price: $3,000–$10,000" />
        <outline text="Template-able: Partially — portfolio display is key" />
        <outline text="Speed advantage: Moderate" />
        <outline text="21. &lt;b&gt;Medical Practice Websites&lt;/b&gt;" />
        <outline text="Who pays: Doctors, dentists, specialists, group practices" />
        <outline text="Price: $3,000–$8,000" />
        <outline text="Template-able: YES — providers, services, locations, insurance, contact" />
        <outline text="Speed advantage: Moderate" />
        <outline text="Volume: ~250K physician practices in US" />
        <outline text="22. &lt;b&gt;Individual Provider / Doctor Profile Pages&lt;/b&gt;" />
        <outline text="Who pays: Healthcare systems, group practices" />
        <outline text="Price: $500–$1,500 per provider" />
        <outline text="Template-able: Highly" />
        <outline text="Speed advantage: HIGH — new hires need pages fast" />
        <outline text="23. &lt;b&gt;Wellness / Med Spa / Aesthetic Practice Sites&lt;/b&gt;" />
        <outline text="Who pays: Med spa owners, aesthetic practitioners" />
        <outline text="Price: $2,000–$6,000" />
        <outline text="Template-able: YES" />
        <outline text="Speed advantage: Moderate" />
        <outline text="Growing fast — one of the hottest healthcare sub-segments" />
        <outline text="24. &lt;b&gt;General Contractor / Construction Company Sites&lt;/b&gt;" />
        <outline text="Who pays: GCs, builders, remodelers" />
        <outline text="Price: $1,500–$5,000" />
        <outline text="Template-able: Highly — projects gallery, services, about, contact" />
        <outline text="Speed advantage: Moderate" />
        <outline text="Volume: ~750K construction firms in US" />
        <outline text="25. &lt;b&gt;Home Services / Trade Business Sites&lt;/b&gt; (plumbers, electricians, HVAC, roofers)" />
        <outline text="Who pays: Trade business owners" />
        <outline text="Price: $1,000–$3,000" />
        <outline text="Template-able: Highly" />
        <outline text="Speed advantage: HIGH — many need sites quickly when starting/rebranding" />
        <outline text="26. &lt;b&gt;Commercial Real Estate Development Project Pages&lt;/b&gt;" />
        <outline text="Who pays: CRE developers, investment firms" />
        <outline text="Price: $5,000–$15,000" />
        <outline text="Template-able: Partially" />
        <outline text="Speed advantage: HIGH — tied to capital raising timelines" />
        <outline text="SALES &amp; B2B ($700M+)" />
        <outline text="27. &lt;b&gt;Digital Sales Proposals / Proposal Microsites&lt;/b&gt;" />
        <outline text="Who pays: Sales teams, agencies, consultancies" />
        <outline text="Price: $1,000–$3,000 per proposal site" />
        <outline text="Template-able: YES — but each is customized per prospect" />
        <outline text="Speed advantage: CRITICAL — needed within days of prospect meeting" />
        <outline text="Emerging category with huge growth" />
        <outline text="28. &lt;b&gt;Case Study / Customer Story Pages&lt;/b&gt;" />
        <outline text="Who pays: B2B marketing teams" />
        <outline text="Price: $1,000–$3,000 each" />
        <outline text="Template-able: Highly" />
        <outline text="Speed advantage: HIGH" />
        <outline text="29. &lt;b&gt;Partner / Channel Marketing Pages&lt;/b&gt;" />
        <outline text="Who pays: Tech companies, SaaS vendors for their channel partners" />
        <outline text="Price: $1,000–$3,000 each, but in bulk" />
        <outline text="Template-able: Highly" />
        <outline text="Speed advantage: HIGH" />
        <outline text="30. &lt;b&gt;Product One-Pagers / Sell Sheets (web versions)&lt;/b&gt;" />
        <outline text="Who pays: Product marketing, sales enablement" />
        <outline text="Price: $500–$2,000" />
        <outline text="Template-able: YES" />
        <outline text="Speed advantage: HIGH" />
        <outline text="INVESTMENT &amp; FINANCE ($500M+)" />
        <outline text="31. &lt;b&gt;Fund Marketing / Investor Relations Pages&lt;/b&gt;" />
        <outline text="Who pays: PE firms, VC firms, hedge funds, real estate funds" />
        <outline text="Price: $5,000–$15,000" />
        <outline text="Template-able: Partially — compliance matters but structure repeats" />
        <outline text="Speed advantage: Moderate" />
        <outline text="32. &lt;b&gt;Deal / Investment Opportunity Pages&lt;/b&gt;" />
        <outline text="Who pays: Syndicators, fund managers, deal sponsors" />
        <outline text="Price: $2,000–$5,000" />
        <outline text="Template-able: YES — deal summary, terms, team, docs" />
        <outline text="Speed advantage: CRITICAL — deal windows are short" />
        <outline text="33. &lt;b&gt;Family Office / Wealth Management Firm Sites&lt;/b&gt;" />
        <outline text="Who pays: Family offices, RIAs" />
        <outline text="Price: $3,000–$10,000" />
        <outline text="Template-able: YES" />
        <outline text="Speed advantage: Moderate" />
        <outline text="HR &amp; RECRUITING ($600M+)" />
        <outline text="34. &lt;b&gt;Career / Recruiting Landing Pages&lt;/b&gt;" />
        <outline text="Who pays: HR departments, talent acquisition teams" />
        <outline text="Price: $2,000–$5,000" />
        <outline text="Template-able: YES — culture, benefits, open roles, team photos" />
        <outline text="Speed advantage: HIGH — hiring pushes have urgency" />
        <outline text="35. &lt;b&gt;Employer Brand Microsites&lt;/b&gt;" />
        <outline text="Who pays: Large companies, fast-growing startups" />
        <outline text="Price: $5,000–$15,000" />
        <outline text="Template-able: Partially" />
        <outline text="Speed advantage: Moderate" />
        <outline text="36. &lt;b&gt;Recruiting Event / Job Fair Pages&lt;/b&gt;" />
        <outline text="Who pays: HR teams, recruiting agencies" />
        <outline text="Price: $500–$2,000" />
        <outline text="Template-able: Highly" />
        <outline text="Speed advantage: CRITICAL" />
        <outline text="NONPROFITS &amp; FUNDRAISING ($400M+)" />
        <outline text="40. &lt;b&gt;Fundraising Campaign Pages&lt;/b&gt;" />
        <outline text="Who pays: Nonprofits, foundations" />
        <outline text="Price: $1,000–$5,000" />
        <outline text="Template-able: YES — story, impact, donation CTA (link to external processor)" />
        <outline text="Speed advantage: HIGH — tied to giving seasons, emergencies" />
        <outline text="41. &lt;b&gt;Annual Report / Impact Report Sites&lt;/b&gt;" />
        <outline text="Who pays: Nonprofits, foundations, ESG-focused companies" />
        <outline text="Price: $3,000–$10,000" />
        <outline text="Template-able: Partially — data visualization, storytelling" />
        <outline text="Speed advantage: Moderate" />
        <outline text="42. &lt;b&gt;Gala / Benefit Event Sites&lt;/b&gt;" />
        <outline text="Who pays: Nonprofits, event committees" />
        <outline text="Price: $1,000–$3,000" />
        <outline text="Template-able: Highly" />
        <outline text="Speed advantage: HIGH" />
        <outline text="46. &lt;b&gt;Book Launch / Author Pages&lt;/b&gt;" />
        <outline text="Who pays: Authors, publishers" />
        <outline text="Price: $1,000–$3,000" />
        <outline text="Template-able: YES" />
        <outline text="Speed advantage: HIGH — tied to publication date" />
        <outline text="PERSONAL BRANDING &amp; FREELANCE ($300M+)" />
        <outline text="47. &lt;b&gt;Personal Brand / Portfolio Sites&lt;/b&gt;" />
        <outline text="Who pays: Executives, consultants, speakers, freelancers" />
        <outline text="Price: $1,000–$5,000" />
        <outline text="Template-able: YES" />
        <outline text="Speed advantage: Moderate" />
        <outline text="Volume: Massive — millions of professionals want these" />
        <outline text="48. &lt;b&gt;Speaker / Keynote One-Sheets (as web pages)&lt;/b&gt;" />
        <outline text="Who pays: Speakers, speaker bureaus" />
        <outline text="Price: $500–$2,000" />
        <outline text="Template-able: Highly" />
        <outline text="Speed advantage: HIGH" />
        <outline text="49. &lt;b&gt;Coach / Consultant Service Pages&lt;/b&gt;" />
        <outline text="Who pays: Life coaches, business coaches, consultants" />
        <outline text="Price: $1,000–$3,000" />
        <outline text="Template-able: YES" />
        <outline text="Speed advantage: HIGH" />
        <outline text="**54. &lt;b&gt;Obituary / Memorial Pages&lt;/b&gt; (premium/custom) [&amp;lt;=&amp;gt;]** this is actually really really interesting" />
        <outline text="Who pays: Families, funeral homes" />
        <outline text="Price: $300–$1,500" />
        <outline text="Template-able: Highly" />
        <outline text="Speed advantage: CRITICAL — needed within 24-48 hours" />
        <outline text="---" />
        <outline text="Very interesting sorted list">
          <outline text="MARKET SPEND" />
          <outline text="Here's my ranking of where the most total dollars flow, considering (volume x price x frequency):" />
          <outline text="RankTypeEst. Annual US MarketWhy It Ranks&lt;b&gt;1Campaign Landing Pages&lt;/b&gt;~$3B+Millions created annually. Every brand, every campaign, every season. Agencies charge $2K-$8K each and create dozens per client per year.&lt;b&gt;2Real Estate Agent Personal Sites&lt;/b&gt;~$1.5B+1.5M agents, high churn/rebrand rate, $1.5K-$5K each. Brokerages often pay too.&lt;b&gt;3Small Business Websites (services/trades)&lt;/b&gt;~$1.2B+Plumbers, contractors, salons, auto shops — hundreds of thousands of small businesses buying $1K-$5K sites annually.&lt;b&gt;4Restaurant Websites&lt;/b&gt;~$800M+60K new + hundreds of thousands refreshing. Simple structure but everyone needs one.&lt;b&gt;5Law Firm / Attorney Sites&lt;/b&gt;~$700M+High price point ($3K-$10K), 450K firms, and lawyers actually pay for quality.&lt;b&gt;6Medical/Dental Practice Sites&lt;/b&gt;~$600M+250K+ practices, $3K-$8K, plus ongoing provider page needs.&lt;b&gt;7Property Listing / Luxury Single-Property Sites&lt;/b&gt;~$500M+High volume in luxury segment, critical speed need, recurring (every new listing).&lt;b&gt;8New Development / Pre-Construction Sites&lt;/b&gt;~$500M+High price point ($5K-$25K), thousands of projects annually.&lt;b&gt;9Conference / Event Sites&lt;/b&gt;~$450M+Hundreds of thousands of events per year, each needs a site, recurring annually.&lt;b&gt;10Wedding Websites (custom/premium)&lt;/b&gt;~$400M+2M weddings/year, growing desire for custom over Zola/Knot templates.&lt;b&gt;11Career / Recruiting Pages&lt;/b&gt;~$350M+Every growing company needs them, often refreshed quarterly.&lt;b&gt;12Personal Brand / Portfolio Sites&lt;/b&gt;~$350M+Massive volume of professionals, speakers, execs. Lower price but huge quantity.&lt;b&gt;13Product Launch / Microsite Pages&lt;/b&gt;~$300M+High price point, every product launch at mid-to-large companies.&lt;b&gt;14Fund Marketing / Deal Pages (Finance)&lt;/b&gt;~$300M+Lower volume but very high price point, and financial firms pay premium.&lt;b&gt;15Nonprofit Campaign / Fundraising Pages&lt;/b&gt;~$250M+1.5M nonprofits in US, most need campaign-specific pages regularly." />
          <outline text="KEY INSIGHTS FOR AN AI-POWERED SAME-DAY SERVICE&lt;b&gt;Biggest opportunities where your service demolishes the status quo:&lt;/b&gt;1. &lt;b&gt;Campaign Landing Pages&lt;/b&gt; — The #1 opportunity. Agencies charge $3K-$8K and take 2-4 weeks. A same-day, $200-$500 AI-generated landing page is a category killer. Marketers are the most volume-sensitive buyers.2. &lt;b&gt;Property Listing Sites&lt;/b&gt; — Speed is everything. A luxury listing agent who can have a stunning single-property site live the same day as photos are ready? That's a game-changer vs. waiting a week.3. &lt;b&gt;Event Sites&lt;/b&gt; — Conferences, galas, weddings. All time-sensitive. All follow predictable structures. All are currently overpriced for what they are.4. &lt;b&gt;Real Estate Agent Sites&lt;/b&gt; — New agents, agents switching brokerages, seasonal refreshes. Template-perfect use case with spreadsheet-backed listings.5. &lt;b&gt;Restaurant Sites&lt;/b&gt; — The structure is completely predictable (menu, hours, location, photos). Restaurants hate paying $3K+ for something this simple.6. &lt;b&gt;Sales Proposal Sites&lt;/b&gt; — Emerging category. Sales teams would LOVE to send prospects a custom mini-site instead of a PDF. Speed is the entire value prop.&lt;b&gt;The sweet spot for your AI service is: pages that are (a) structurally predictable, (b) currently overpriced, (c) time-sensitive, and (d) ordered by non-technical buyers.&lt;/b&gt; That's landing pages, real estate, events, restaurants, and professional services — in that order." />
        </outline>
        <outline text="---" />
        <outline text="TOP 15 TRIGGERS — Ranked by Urgency + Willingness to Pay + AI Same-Day Advantage" />
        <outline text="Tier 1 — Strongest Opportunities" />
        <outline text="1. Someone Dies — Memorial Page" />
        <outline text="Urgency: Extreme (same day). No one plans for this. Funeral homes charge $200+ for basic obituary pages. Current alternatives feel generic and impersonal. A custom memorial page that captures who this person was, built from a conversation while grief is raw, is deeply valuable. Price: $75–$200. Volume: ~3M deaths/year in the US alone." />
        <outline text="2. Just Started a Business — Need a Website Today" />
        <outline text="Urgency: High. They filed an LLC, they're telling people, and the first question is &quot;what's your website?&quot; Every day without a site is lost credibility. Current path: Squarespace takes days of learning, hiring a designer takes weeks and $2K+. Same-day custom site from a conversation is a game-changer. Price: $100–$300. Massive volume." />
        <outline text="3. Big Client Meeting / Pitch Tomorrow — Need to Look Legit" />
        <outline text="Urgency: Extreme (tonight). Consultants, freelancers, and small agencies scramble to build credibility before a make-or-break meeting. The ROI is enormous — a $200 site could win a $20K contract. Nothing else can produce a custom, professional site overnight. Price: $100–$300." />
        <outline text="4. Product Launch on a Deadline" />
        <outline text="Urgency: High (date-locked). Startups, indie makers, and small companies constantly need launch pages. The launch date doesn't move. Current path: hire a freelancer (weeks, $1K+) or DIY (days). Same-day from a conversation is a clear win. Price: $100–$500." />
        <outline text="5. Freelancer / Consultant Needs a Portfolio NOW" />
        <outline text="Urgency: High. Triggered by &quot;can you send me your portfolio?&quot; or a job application. The opportunity has a shelf life of hours. Price: $50–$200. Very large addressable market." />
        <outline text="Tier 2 — Strong Opportunities" />
        <outline text="6. Running for Local Office" />
        <outline text="Urgency: High (filing deadline triggers it). Thousands of local races annually. Candidates are not tech people. A campaign page with platform, bio, donate link — built from one conversation — is dramatically better than what most local candidates have. Price: $100–$300." />
        <outline text="7. Crisis Communication / PR Response" />
        <outline text="Urgency: Extreme (hours). When something goes wrong publicly, companies need a dedicated response page fast. Agencies charge thousands and take days. Price: $200–$500. Lower volume but very high willingness to pay." />
        <outline text="8. Fundraiser for a Crisis (Medical Emergency, Disaster)" />
        <outline text="Urgency: Extreme (same day). GoFundMe is limited in storytelling. A companion page with the full story creates trust and drives more donations. Price: $50–$150." />
        <outline text="9. Wedding Website" />
        <outline text="Urgency: Medium-high (procrastinated then suddenly urgent). Huge market. Zola/The Knot exist but are generic. Couples want their aesthetic. Price: $50–$150. Enormous volume." />
        <outline text="10. Event Landing Page (Conference, Workshop, Community Event)" />
        <outline text="Urgency: High (date-locked). Event organizers always underestimate how long the website takes. A custom event page with the right vibe, built same-day, solves a real pain point. Price: $100–$300." />
        <outline text="Tier 3 — Good Opportunities" />
        <outline text="11. Selling a House FSBO" />
        <outline text="Urgency: High. Homeowners saving $15K+ in agent commissions will gladly spend $100–$200 on a beautiful single-property page. Price: $100–$200." />
        <outline text="12. Author / Book Launch" />
        <outline text="Urgency: Medium-high (pub date is fixed). Authors are often not technical. A custom page matching the book's aesthetic is exactly right. Price: $75–$250." />
        <outline text="13. Speaker Page (&quot;Send Me Your Speaker Page&quot;)" />
        <outline text="Urgency: High (immediate ask). Not having one loses the gig. Price: $75–$200." />
        <outline text="14. Course / Workshop Launch" />
        <outline text="Urgency: Medium-high (enrollment deadline). Creators need sales pages but current path is Kajabi ($150/mo) or hire a designer ($1K+). Price: $75–$250." />
        <outline text="15. Nonprofit Just Incorporated" />
        <outline text="Urgency: High. Need to start fundraising immediately. Donors expect a website. Price: $75–$250." />
        <outline text="Why These Top 15 Win" />
        <outline text="The common thread:" />
        <outline text="1. The trigger is external and the deadline is real — something happened that created urgency" />
        <outline text="2. The person who needs it is not a web designer — they're grieving, launching, scrambling" />
        <outline text="3. Custom matters but perfection doesn't — &quot;professional and personal&quot; is the bar" />
        <outline text="4. Current alternatives are too slow, too expensive, or too generic — this service fills a gap nothing else does" />
        <outline text="5. Same-day delivery is a genuine differentiator — the value of the site decays rapidly with time. Speed is the product.">
          <outline text="1.  asked &amp;quot;what's your website?&amp;quot;, business just incorporated. Extreme urgency. The overnight custom site as a product." />
          <outline text="The trigger-events agent surfaced something interesting: a lot of the highest-urgency demand comes from moments where speed IS the entire product. Not &amp;quot;I should probably get a website someday&amp;quot; but &amp;quot;I need this by TUESDAY.&amp;quot; That's a different positioning than &amp;quot;we do beautiful custom work.&amp;quot; It's &amp;quot;we deliver custom overnight.&amp;quot;What catches your eye here? The property listing site thing feels alive to me — it's narrow, repeatable, high-money, and structurally very similar to what you already proved you can do." />
        </outline>
        <outline text="---" />
        <outline text="Event venues (wedding venues, banquet halls, conference centers) — This one keeps surfacing and I think it's real. Bookings are $5K-$50K each. Most venue sites are embarrassingly bad. The structure is completely predictable (spaces, capacity, packages, gallery, inquiry form). And here's the kicker: it connects to the wedding business. Venue → refers couples → your wedding stationery/website service. It's a lead channel AND a revenue stream. And the AI feature works perfectly here: &amp;quot;Ask about this venue&amp;quot; — capacity, catering options, availability, what's included." />
        <outline text="Daycare/preschool sites — Parents research obsessively. One enrolled child = $12K-$24K/year in revenue. There are 500K+ childcare businesses in the US. Most have terrible websites. The structure is completely standardized. These owners are too busy running the daycare to deal with websites. This is a surprisingly big, badly underserved market." />
        <outline text="Tour operators / experience companies — Charter fishing, walking tours, adventure guides, cooking classes. Tourists book online. Very similar to Airbnb structurally (photos, description, what to expect, booking link) but for experiences. The AI chat feature is perfect: &quot;what should I wear?&quot;, &quot;is it family-friendly?&quot;, &quot;what's the cancellation policy?&quot;" />
        <outline text="Executive/career transition sites — C-suite people leaving a role, becoming board members, advisors, speakers. They have MONEY ($50K-$300K board seats). They have NO time. They need to look established yesterday. Very standard structure. This is a small niche but very high ticket." />
        <outline text="Proposal/pitch microsites — Agencies sending a custom site instead of a PDF to pitch a $100K+ deal. Recurring (same agency, many pitches). Clear ROI. But this is very B2B and might not be where you want to play." />
        <outline text="Beyond these, honestly? Most of what came up is variations on what we already know — professional services sites, trades/contractors, photographers, etc. The landscape of &quot;types of websites people pay for&quot; is actually not that surprising once you've seen it. The money is in the niches we've already identified plus these few new ones." />
        <outline text="The thing that keeps standing out to me: event venues feels like the most interesting new addition, specifically because of the wedding connection. What do you think?" />
      </outline>
    </outline>
  </body>
</opml>